Fix batch/shell startup scripts: root .env distribution + absolute paths

Problems found in terminal log:
- Batch file checked Backend\.env but user placed .env at project root → stub
  created, real credentials ignored
- `cd frontend && npm install --silent && cd ..` in if-block drifted working
  directory; subsequent `start` commands ran from wrong path
- `--silent` masked npm install errors; no visible feedback
- `start` commands used relative paths that break after any cd

Fixes:
- setup_env.py: new Python helper that reads root .env and writes:
  * Backend-specific vars → Backend/.env
  * NEXT_PUBLIC_* vars   → frontend/.env.local
  * EXPO_PUBLIC_* vars   → mobile/.env
- start_app.bat: full rewrite
  * Detects root .env and runs setup_env.py first
  * Uses %~dp0 (absolute batch dir) for all paths
  * Uses pushd/popd instead of cd/cd.. chains
  * Uses `call npm install` (required in Windows batch)
  * Removed --silent so errors are visible
  * start commands use `cd /d "%ROOT%\..."` absolute paths
  * pause >nul at end keeps launcher window open
- start_app.sh: matching fixes
  * Detects root .env and runs setup_env.py
  * Uses subshell (cd ... && cmd) for package installs
  * wait 20s boot time before opening browser
